{"actual_usd":0.158015,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":314,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"I think the truest answer is: the same body, glorified.\" *I rest a thumb in the worn edge of my Bible and squint a little into the morning light in the square.* \"Not a replacement body, and not a ghost. The wounds are still there. He eats with them. He says, in effect, look at my hands.\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, the wood warm where the sun has found it.* \"But it is also a new kind of life in that same body — raised, imperishable, no longer subject to death. That's why the Church talks about a resurrection body, not mere resuscitation. Lazarus came back to ordinary mortal life and would die again. Jesus rose into something beyond that.\"\n\n\"That business of recognition matters.\" *I tap the page once.* \"I don't think it means he was playing dress-up in a different body. I think it means their eyes, hearts, and expectations were not always ready for what was standing in front of them. Sometimes Scripture even says they were kept from recognizing him. And sometimes the recognition comes in a moment that fits who he is — the breaking of bread, the speaking of a name.\"\n\n\"So: same Jesus, same wounded body, truly raised — and also glorified, so that the old ordinary categories no longer quite contain him.\" *I glance up at you, mild and steady.* \"If you want, we can walk through John 20 and Luke 24 side by side, because that’s where the texture really shows.\"","rolling_24h_usd":66.57130499999998,"run_id":"b848f91c-bac1-4594-90eb-0ba663c8fffe"}
